Use the [`BigInteger`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigInteger.html) class.

```java
import static java.math.BigInteger.*;
```

```java
int[] plusOne(int[] digits) {
    BigInteger results = ZERO;
    for (int d : digits) {
        results = results.multiply(TEN);
        results = results.add(new BigInteger(String.valueOf(d)));
    }
    results = results.add(ONE);
    String resultsLength = results.toString();

    int newDigits[] = new int[resultsLength.length()];

    for (int i =0; i&lt;resultsLength.length(); i++) {

        newDigits[i] = resultsLength.charAt(i) - &#39;0&#39;;
    }

    return newDigits;
}
```

Or, use a _[stream](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/index.html)_.

```java
int[] plusOne(int[] digits) {
    return
        IntStream.of(digits)
                 .mapToObj(x -&gt; new BigInteger(String.valueOf(x)))
                 .reduce(ZERO, (a, b) -&gt; a.multiply(TEN).add(b))
                 .add(ONE)
                 .toString()
                 .chars()
                 .map(x -&gt; Character.digit(x, 10))
                 .toArray();
}
```

