Start by containing the data.&amp;nbsp; An _[array](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/arrays.html)_, for each set, should suffice.\
I&#39;m using an [`Integer`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Integer.html) _array_, rather than a _primitive_ [`int`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html) _array_, as to utilize the [`Collections#shuffle`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Collections.html#shuffle(java.util.List)) method.\
This will produce a set of unique values.

```java
Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
int i, n = 5;
Integer[] R = new Integer[99], G = new Integer[n];
for (i = 1; i &lt; 100; i++) R[i - 1] = i;
Collections.shuffle(Arrays.asList(R));
R = Arrays.copyOfRange(R, 0, n);
for (i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
    out.printf(&quot;guess %d:  &quot;, i + 1);
    G[i] = in.nextInt();
}
```

From here, traverse _G_, and sub-traverse _R_, qualifying any matching numbers.\
You could even use another _array_, or a [`List`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html), to contain the values.\
Although, since you&#39;re only printing the values, a [`StringBuilder`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/StringBuilder.html) class would be a simpler approach.

```java
StringBuilder s = new StringBuilder();
for (int g : G)
    for (int r : R)
        if (g == r) {
            if (!s.isEmpty()) s.append(&quot;, &quot;);
            s.append(g);
        }
out.println(&quot;R = &quot; + Arrays.toString(R));
out.println(&quot;G = &quot; + Arrays.toString(G));
out.println(&quot;matching numbers:  &quot; + s);
```

Here is an example usage.

```none
guess 1:  55
guess 2:  24
guess 3:  93
guess 4:  1
guess 5:  2
R = [50, 24, 78, 55, 93]
G = [55, 24, 93, 1, 2]
matching numbers:  55, 24, 93
```

The easiest way, imo, is to use a [HashSet](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/HashSet.html#HashSet()).  Sets cannot hold duplicates so it would be perfect for lottery numbers.

- One set has the winning numbers.
- The other set has the users choices.
- using the [retainAll()](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Set.html#retainAll(java.util.Collection)) method only keeps the user numbers that were the same as the winningNumbers.  
```
static int NCHOICES = 5;
Set&lt;Integer&gt; winningNumber = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(Set.of(23, 32, 43, 54, 65));
Set&lt;Integer&gt; user = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
for (int i = 1; i &lt;= NCHOICES; i++) {
    System.out.printf(&quot;Please enter #%d: &quot;, i);
    int numb = input.nextInt();
    if (numb &gt; LIMIT || !user.add(numb)) {
        System.out.printf(&quot;Number %d already added or too large, try again.%n&quot;, numb);
        i--;
    }
}
user.retainAll(winningNumber);
System.out.printf(&quot;The user picked %d correctly%n&quot;, user.size());
System.out.printf(&quot;They are %s%n&quot;, user);
```
If this input were `41, 23, 62, 4, 32`, the output would be
```
Please enter #1: 41
Please enter #2: 23
Please enter #3: 62
Please enter #4: 4
Please enter #5: 32
The user picked 2 correctly
They are [32, 23]
```
To populate the `winningNUmbers` set, you can do it as follows.
- define a size LIMIT of the number to be chosen.
- Allocate an `ArrayList` to hold the numbers from 1 to LIMIT.
- then populate the list using a loop.
- then each time you want to create a net set of winning numbers.
   - clear the existing `winningNumber` set.
   - Shuffle the list.
   - And add a `sublist` of the first `NCHOICES` numbers to the set.
```
static int LIMIT = 100;
List&lt;Integer&gt; lotteryNumbers = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
for (int i = 1; i &lt; LIMIT; i++) {
    lotteryNumbers.add(i);
}
winningNumbers.clear();
Collections.shuffle(lotteryNumbers);
winningNumbers.addAll(lotteryNumbers.subList(0,NCHOICES));
System.out.println(winningNumbers);
```
prints something like
```
[49, 34, 54, 39, 57]
```
Note that you only need to create the List of numbers once.  Just shuffle it each time right before you want to populate the winningNumbers set.

