Your code couldn&#39;t be compiled, since classes like `Question` and `POOTrivia` were missing.

I went ahead and created a complete GUI that might do what you&#39;re looking for.

[![Example GUI][1]][1]

# Explanation

Oracle has a helpful tutorial, [Creating a GUI With Swing](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/index.html).  Skip the Learning Swing with the NetBeans IDE section.

When I create a Swing GUI, I use the [model-view-controller][2] (MVC) pattern.  This pattern allows me to separate my concerns and focus on one part of the application at a time.

It looked like you attempted to do this, but your model was not cleanly separated from your view.

A Swing model consists of one or more plain Java getter/setter classes.

A Swing view consists of one `JFrame` and as many `JPanels` and `JDialogs` as you need.

Each Swing `Action` or `Listener` is a controller.  There&#39;s usually not one controller to &quot;rule them all&quot;.

