Even though the lazy fetch type is specified for associated entities, the entire `Customer` object is returned from the endpoint, leading to the initialization of lazy-loaded fields during serialization.

You can use [projections][1], to retrieve only needed properties, since Spring Data allows modeling dedicated return types, to more selectively retrieve partial views of the managed aggregates.

For each response type, it&#39;s preferable to provide a separate endpoint. For example, to provide an endpoint for returning a customer with accounts, you can do the following.

First, declare an interface projection that exposes accessor methods for the properties to be read.

```java
public interface CustomerWithAccountsProjection {
  String getFirstName();

  String getLasName();

  String getEmail();

  Set&lt;AccountProjection&gt; getAccounts();

  interface AccountProjection {
    Long getId();

    BigDecimal getBalance();

    CurrencyProjection getCurrency();
  }

  interface CurrencyProjection {
    Long getId();
  }
}
```
&gt; The important bit here is that the properties defined here exactly
&gt; match properties in the aggregate root.

Then declare a query method in the repository.

```java
interface CustomerRepository extends JpaRepository&lt;Customer, Long&gt; {
    Optional&lt;CustomerWithAccountsProjection&gt; findCustomerWithAccountsById(Long id);
}
```

&gt; The query execution engine creates proxy instances of that interface
&gt; at runtime for each element returned and forwards calls to the exposed
&gt; methods to the target object.

That&#39;s it. For other use cases, just declare a new interface and method in the repository. 

With this approach, there&#39;s no need to pollute entity models with serialization-related annotations such as `@JsonIgnore`. Additionally, lazy-loaded associations would not be fetched unless declared in a projection.

If you need a more flexible API, I suggest [GraphQL][2].


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/jpa/reference/repositories/projections.html
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-graphql/reference/

